It's what you don't get that counts

The platform here istechnical, my personal opinions are to be kept at an absolute minimum. (You're welcome).

Methods

the charlottesville council agenda is being used to start the conversation. These are real issues that council will make decisions on.

Privacy & Security

This is a public forum. Usingthis site is like showing up at City Hall. If youwouldn't say something in public, please don't say it here. That said I'm doing my best to run a decent site, at leastaccording to SSL Labs. Please let me know if you have any other standards you feel should be met.

18F API Compliance

18Fis a governmental agency founded in 2014 to help standardize governmental data delivery. They have an API, and this site is focused on compliance.

Welcome

Vote for You!

The goal of this website is to make "crowdsourcing" political decisions simpler and providea more directdemocracy

I'mrunningfor Charlottesville City Council in2015- my platform is that whatever people decide on this website will determine my vote. I will not act on my personalopinions... you're welcome.

The hope is that other city council members may also be able to use this site to get feedback and better understand their constituents.

How this site works...

1) Register below- we manually review each person, so it may take a few hours to get registered

2) Create new polls on the site - get community feedback

3) Vote on issues - give city councilfeedback on all the issues

Aloha

Anson (me) is the person building this site and running for city council. I've been in the c-villagesince 1996,having moved to the big city from Lexington, Va..

Nerd notes...

For thelocalweb developer -I'm working on a RESTful API releasing JSON & XML for public data, and an oauth server - so 3rd party app builders are welcome to makecontactfor authorization.

About the money.

Did you know city council folks make $14K a year? I would like to implement some data mining features (geoserver among other things) that will probably crush my present servers... also I would like to keep up with feature requests to make the user experience as tight as possible.

Scaling

How far can this scale? What happens when a website runs for city council... what if two websites are competing? Could you have a congressperson take orders from the masses?

As Dave Norris pointed out the scale on this is probably a moving target - and what works for Charlottesville may not provide anopportunity for Waynesboro. On the other hand it's clearly the direction technology is going - and while I'm skeptical as to whether the world needs another instagram, another facebook, or another pinterest there should definitely be room for clearer decision making... going in to rooms and pulling levers is so second millenium.
